SIMPLE: dactyl
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: dactyl
<hw>dac"tyl</hw> <pr>(d⟦acr⟧k"t⟦icr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>dactylus</ets>, Gr. <grk>da`ktylos</grk> a finger, a dactyl. Cf.
<er>Digit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>A poetical
foot of three syllables (⟦mdash⟧ ⟦cre⟧ ⟦cre⟧), one long followed by two
short, or one accented followed by two unaccented; <as>as, L.
<it>t⟦eum⟧gm⟦icr⟧n⟦ecr⟧</it>, E. <it>mer⟦bprime⟧ciful</it>; -- so called
from the similarity of its arrangement to that of the joints of a
finger.</as></def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>dactyle</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A finger or toe; a
digit.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The claw or terminal joint of a leg of an
insect or crustacean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>dactylar</ent>⟦br⟧
